# Template for the binary package control file. @VERSION@ and @INSTALLED_SIZE@
# are substituted at build time and every '#' line is stripped, so comments here
# never reach the built package.
#
# Depends deliberations:
#
#   systemd   — the package ships a unit and its postinst enables it. Without
#               systemd the package installs a file nothing will ever read.
#
#   hostname  — /etc/qubes-rpc/qubesair.Ping falls back to `hostname` when
#               QUBESAIR_REMOTE_NAME is unset. It is priority:required on Debian
#               so it is present in practice, but it is not Essential, and the
#               failure it causes shows up only when a probe is answered — long
#               after install, looking like a transport fault.
#
#   qemu-guest-agent — deliberately NOT a dependency. It is a hypervisor
#               concern, not an agent concern: terraform needs it to learn the
#               VM's address, and cloud-init already installs it via the
#               packages: stanza in RenderAgentUserData. Depending on it here
#               would mean this package can only be installed on QEMU guests,
#               and on anything else it would leave a permanently failing unit
#               behind. Two owners of the same fact is worse than one.
Package: qubes-air-agent
Version: @VERSION@
Architecture: amd64
Maintainer: Qubes Air <slarlenesu@gmail.com>
Section: admin
Priority: optional
Installed-Size: @INSTALLED_SIZE@
Depends: systemd, hostname
Homepage: https://github.com/slchris/qubes-air
Description: Qubes Air RemoteVM agent
 Gives a non-Qubes remote host qrexec semantics without Xen vchan, so that a
 cloud or LAN VM can serve as a RemoteVM for a Qubes Air deployment.
 .
 The agent listens for the local relay over mutual TLS and executes the qrexec
 services installed under /etc/qubes-rpc. Its certificates and its
 /etc/qubes-air/agent.env are delivered separately by the console via
 cloud-init; the unit is enabled on install but not started, because without
 those files the agent will — correctly — refuse to run.
